data.content:
**In .NET 11, all your sync Cosmos DB calls will throw at runtime â€” the sync-over-async opt-in has been fully removed.**

In EF Core 10 you could opt in to sync-over-async, but EF Core 11 eliminates that escape hatch entirely. Every method in your `ProductRepository` is affected:

| Breaks | Fix |
|--------|-----|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First(...)` | `await FirstAsync(...)` |
| `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

Your repository needs to become fully async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
        => await _context.Products.ToListAsync();

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
        => await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
        => await _context.Products.CountAsync();

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

All callers must be updated to `await` these methods as well â€” this typically ripples up through controllers/services. There is no workaround; the Cosmos DB provider enforces async-only I/O in .NET 11.
